  <discussion>Niphotrichum pygmaeum is known only from a few collections in British Columbia and Washington.  It is the rarest and smallest species of the genus, readily known by its awn, which is epapillose or only slightly papillose at the base, percurrent costa, which is not situated in a channel, small and flat auricles, and opaque distal laminal cells that are yellow and fairly densely and conspicuously papillose.</discussion>
